                  <h3 class="headline-3-text" style="text-align: justify">What is Remote Sensing?</h3>
                  <div class="body-1-text" style="text-align: justify">  Remote sensing is the process of observing the physical characteristics of an object/area by measuring its reflected and emitted radiation at a distance from the targeted object/area, typically by sensors mounted on aircrafts or satellites.
                     Primarily remote sensors can either be active sensors which provide their own source of energy and emits radiations in the direction of target object/area. Some of the active sensors are Laser altimeter, Lidar, Radar etc. On the other hand most passive sensor systems operate in the visible, infrared, thermal infrared and microwave portions of the electromagnetic spectrum. Remote sensing has a wide range of applications in many different fields like natural resource management, hazard assessment, coastal monitoring and mapping, environmental management and conservation etc.
                  </div>
                  <h3 class="headline-3-text" style="text-align: justify">Remote Sensing Services</h3>
                  <div class="body-1-text" style="text-align: justify"> We provide a range of Remote Sensing and image interpretation services that can help any organisation to leverage the benefits from satellite and aerial imagery. We use freely available satellite data used varies for freely available data such as Landsat series of data and Sentinel, ASTER, LISS-3 and MODIS data sets. Apart from the freely available data, high resolution satellite data can be acquired depending on the requirement of the project. By utilising the many available sources of Remote Sensing data, we can ensure that the best available imagery is analysed to meet your specific requirements.
                  </div>
